post_text:
School starts in 1 week, August 19. Please send a visor, baseball cap or a hat with a rim with your PK-6th grade child. We will provide each child with face shield that clips to the hat. Students will be asked to wear face shields only when they are in a small group or student pair. We hope that wearing a hat will make this a "little" fun for the students. Of course, all students are welcome to wear a facial mask or shield at all times and at the request of a parent.

Teachers will wear face shields or facial masks whenever they are within 6 feet of a student (which will be pretty much all the time )

Also, PK-6 rooms will also have desk shields.

We hope to see you on August 17th at your Back to School appointment. It will be a great opportunity to see and hear about what we are doing to keep our kids safe.

post_text:
At this time, face masks are not required for students, but will be highly recommended when we return to school on August 19th. We have had some wonderful community members and churches sew us masks. These masks can be utilized by any student and/or staff member and will be washed here at school. We will have enough masks for everyone who wishes to wear one. I'd like to thank Barb Dewit, Erica Elliot, Jon Vanderhyde, the Tracy Reformed Church, Alice Nace and Attica Methodist Church for sewing lots and lots of cool masks for Twin Cedars Schools.

If you aren't a sewer, but would like to help supply masks, Mr. Smith found a company that will accept donations and supply masks to our school. Check it out:
https://masks.com/products/twin-cedars-elementary-school-bussey-ia-mask-drive

Students are also welcome to purchase their own masks if that is desired.

Students in K-3 will be offered face shields.

Twin Cedars will be providing Chromebooks to 7th-12th grade students for at home and school use in August. We will nearly have enough devices to provide elementary students with computers as well. In the event of another closing, most elementary students would be sent home with a device. Now we need to consider internet access. The Iowa Department of Education is conducting a survey to identify our need. If you have not completed the survey and you have TC students that live with you, please take a few minutes to answer the questions.
https://tinyurl.com/ycd7h3tf
The survey closes next Wednesday. We still have about 50 families that haven't responded. Thank-you!

post_text: As we say good-bye to 2019-2020, we look ahead to the 2020-2021 school year. We have already begun to plan for what the new normal might look like. We have been directed by the Department of Education to plan, plan, plan. Consider many scenarios. To that end, we are looking for summer sewers (people who sew, not drain pipes). We would like to have face masks on hand, should we need them. Please drop me a message or an email if you are willing and able! Thanks in advance.

#GivingTuesdayNow is a global day of giving and unity, set to take place on May 5, 2020 as an emergency response to the unprecedented need caused by COVID-19. The day is designed to drive an influx of generosity, citizen engagement, business and philanthropy activation, and support for communities and nonprofits around the world. Its a day when we can all come together and give back in all ways, no matter who or where we are.

Let us know if you need help. Send a message to Twin Cedars Elementary Facebook.

post_text:
Everyone is familiar with stained glass. Have you ever wondered why stained glass exists? In a time when people could not read, they needed stories and so stained glass art emerged. How would you tell a story in stained glass?
Here are some directions for making your own "stain glass" from crayons/wax paper: https://www.education.com/download-pdf/activity/3413/

Ask your parents for help. Send Mrs. Roby a picture of your stain glass with an explanation story. She will post it here for others to enjoy.

The Health Well Foundation is providing up to $250 assistance to families for delivered food, medication, diagnostics, transportation and telehealth as a result of COVID-19 risk or incidence.

Applications are done via phone by calling (800) 675-8416.

To qualify for assistance through the COVID-19 Ancillary Fund, the following eligibility requirements must be met:

1. You or a member of your household have a positive diagnosis for COVID-19 OR

2. You or a member of your household are part of a high-risk group that should be especially mindful of contact with COVID-19 (including, but not limited to, immunocompromised patients, the elderly, infants) OR

3. You reside in a geographic area within the United States or one of its territories where COVID-19 is prevalent OR

4. You or a member of your household had a physician or health care provider, or any other official recommend self-quarantine regarding exposure to COVID-19 AND

5. Your income falls within 500% of the Federal Poverty Level.

post_text:
From Mrs. Duinink:
I miss everyone soooooo much!! We have been remodeling/gutting our bathroom, I have been supervising while my husband has been using a jackhammer and tearing out tile and sheetrock. My pets are all so happy I've been home so much (3 dogs: Fonzie, Rascal, Raina, my bird Skittles and Coco the snail). If you want to be active don't forget the YouTube channel Cosmic Kids Yoga, and if you want to meditate do their Peace Outs. Don't forget...... you are kind, you are special, you are smart, you don't give up, you are strong, and Mrs. Duinink likes you very much, Namaste.

To 4th and 5th Grade TC families,

I will be offering an after school Reading Club on Fridays for 3:20-5:00. I will be sending home a note from school to determine interest level and to sign up.
My goal is to give students extra support in their reading skills while making reading fun!

Included:
After School Snack
Reading Skills Work
Story Time and/or Independent Reading Time
Once a Month Friday Fun Day Activity

I look forward to hearing from you!

Mrs. Tammie Andersen

B.A. Elementary Education
Reading Endorsement K-8
Special Education Endorsement K-12
Orton Gillingham Reading Program (Twin Cedars Prof. Dev.)

Email: tlandersen7@yahoo.com

P.S. Reading Club will be limited to 15 participants.

post_text:
Recess Cold Weather Guidelines:

We will go outside everyday for recess if the weather is above 10 degrees.(windchill) If below 10 degrees we will have inside recess.

Between 10 and 40 degrees, children must wear:
Winter coat
Closed shoes or boots
Stocking caps and gloves are recommended

Between 41 and 50 degrees, children must wear:
Winter coat or
heavy jacket over long sleeved clothing
Closed shoes or boots
Stocking caps and gloves are optional

Between 51 and 60 degrees, children must wear:
Winter coat or heavy jacket or sweatshirt/hoodie
Closed shoes or boots
Stocking caps and gloves are optional

Parents and care givers are encouraged to monitor their childrens clothing selections to make sure they are prepared for colder temperatures and are appropriately dressed for outdoor recesses. Each year we collect a large selection of lost clothing that we can not match up with children. Please label your childrens winter clothes so if they misplace them we can get them returned.
